In the sixth Title Actions are divided upon three main principles.

i. According to their content they are divided (a) into real and personal. A real action=is one in which the plaintiff affirms a right in rem, whether dominium (5 1) or a ius in re aliena (5 2); in a personal action his contentiori is that the defendant is under some specific legal obligation to him. ‘Prejudicial ' actionS, in which the issue usually is a question os statue, inay be regarded as a species of the former class: in rem esse videntur, 5 135 and some actions ‘ mix- tam causam obtinere videntur' (5 πο), i.e. are at once both real and personal; these are the iudicia divisoria, such as suits for the partition of an inheritance or other J'oint property, and for the regulation of boundarieS. Cross divisions from this same point of view of content are (b) that which turns upon the plaintiff's more immediate object, according as it is to obtain mere reparation (actiones rei persecutoriae‚ 5 17), as in real actions and those arising ex contractu3 to merely recover a penalty (poenae persecutoriae, 5 18), as in the actio furti 3 or to get compensation and penalty in one (actiones mixtae, 5 19), as in the actions on robbery and under the lex Aquilia, (c) according to the amount of damages recovered, which may be simple (e. g. actions on contract, 5 22), double (e. g. the actio furti nec manifesti, 5 23), triple (5 24) or quadruple (e. g. the actio furti manifesti, 5 25) ς (d) that which depends upon the possibility of the plaintifl's being unable to recover the whole of what is his strict legal due (5 36), owing to the defendant's liability being mere partial or conditional on his means x examples of these are given in 55 36-40.
